elements.2211.03184_2e169ad730e661ec11375169acbcd: Guidelines for Graphics Preparation and Submission
elements.2211.03184_db4468e2cff93005814933bed4c59: Figures that are meant to appear in color, or shades of black/gray
elements.2211.03184_36c2f7911ee464c1e1ce44f79b895: Such figures may include photographs, illustrations, multicolor graphs, and flowcharts.
elements.2211.03184_4cada0cbaa32d051f3e556ad70f2c: Figures that are composed of only black lines and shapes
elements.2211.03184_32b641646b963a21fcea42baaa750: These figures should have no shades or half-tones of gray, only black and white.
elements.2211.03184_42300a707c80c82a96ae75d17869b: Data charts are typically black and white but sometimes include color.
elements.2211.03184_73ae16a64855bf92092e02c3de2cc: Figures compiled of more than one sub-figure presented side-by-side, or stacked
elements.2211.03184_4cb94a53d2011e408e6098e675ea2: If a multipart figure is made up of multiple figure types (one part is lineart, and another is grayscale or color) the figure should meet the stricter guidelines.
elements.2211.03184_563e41b75badb98ed30d00277add7: Format and save your graphics using a suitable graphics processing program that will allow you to create the images as PostScript (PS), Encapsulated PostScript (.EPS), Tagged Image File Format (.TIFF), Portable Document Format (.PDF), or Portable Network Graphics (.PNG); sizes them; and adjusts the resolution settings
elements.2211.03184_563340f502f2f2fd1644b84b5f87d: If you created your source files in one of the following programs you will be able to submit the graphics without converting to a PS, EPS, TIFF, PDF, or PNG file: Microsoft Word, Microsoft PowerPoint, or Microsoft Excel
elements.2211.03184_245102a2c804cbdb8223ee032d590: Though it is not required, it is strongly recommended that these files be saved in PDF format rather than DOC, XLS, or PPT
elements.2211.03184_efd2cbe4d458e248222173140b4a2: Doing so will protect your figures from common font and arrow stroke issues that occur when working on the files across multiple platforms
elements.2211.03184_a0f543adf43fe2d680efc4070c01e: When submitting your final paper, your graphics should all be submitted individually in one of these formats along with the manuscript.
elements.2211.03184_b273c99e473a2e55a9f62f352f257: Most charts, graphs, and tables are one column wide (3.5 inches / 88 millimeters / 21 picas) or page wide (7.16 inches / 181 millimeters / 43 picas)
elements.2211.03184_49d3dc36551c5b36f0421f44659d5: The maximum height a graphic can be is 8.5 inches (216 millimeters / 54 picas)
elements.2211.03184_91069b991f2862903d5d2b89d6cac: When choosing the height of a graphic, please allow space for a caption
elements.2211.03184_0d672d43d38a862b0ac2ad763fa03: Figures can be sized between column and page widths if the author chooses, however it is recommended that figures are not sized less than column width unless absolutely necessary.
elements.2211.03184_997e136128623970a4691c4c89d69: The proper resolution of your figures will depend on the type of figure it is as defined in the
elements.2211.03184_a76ef226d8e2a7ee009cb1b19a816: Author photographs, color, and grayscale figures should be at least 300 dpi
elements.2211.03184_56853cce7882e1d033e88bcebdc30: Line art, including tables should be a minimum of 600 dpi.
elements.2211.03184_42c1a9223aee8de8fbf338188e43f: In order to preserve the figures' integrity across multiple computer platforms, we accept files in the following formats: .EPS/.PDF/.PS
elements.2211.03184_98732c16661731a4cfd84b08719ef: All fonts must be embedded or text converted to outlines in order to achieve the best-quality results.
elements.2211.03184_bdcf5ef5bef05bc8b6f36d6c8d8e4: When preparing your graphics, IEEE suggests that you use of one of the following Open Type fonts: Times New Roman, Helvetica, Arial, Cambria, and Symbol
elements.2211.03184_dfdb10bc99ad716ea379c0e6d5be1: If you are supplying EPS, PS, or PDF files all fonts must be embedded
elements.2211.03184_f39245ef5b012b1e761a466c1aeb5: Some fonts may only be native to your operating system; without the fonts embedded, parts of the graphic may be distorted or missing
elements.2211.03184_328fefc67f9fc1d0c35fc0a887c05: A safe option when finalizing your figures is to strip out the fonts before you save the files, creating
elements.2211.03184_5fcb846e9e2ed49d512f001ce53bf: This converts fonts to artwork what will appear uniformly on any screen.
elements.2211.03184_5b47d15553e081969840f343bae1f: Figure axis labels are often a source of confusion
elements.2211.03184_fbe356d0be0c03b3060a7eb0b6aa0: As an example, write the quantity
elements.2211.03184_312b485febb6ee328ed3030699af9: Do not label axes only with units
elements.2211.03184_2c9dd0133b4a9a49f2dc34d4e5290: As in Fig. 1, for example, write
elements.2211.03184_b1e1793bb5c6cd6691b484d4f5353: Do not label axes with a ratio of quantities and units
elements.2211.03184_e7e7f86653f98d0b77c917400d0c2: because the reader would not know whether the top axis label in Fig. 1 meant 16000 A/m or 0.016 A/m
elements.2211.03184_7a9f08311c44f7c33858c9163ca14: Figure labels should be legible, approximately 8 to 10 point type.
elements.2211.03184_f1be880fd041944b6b3ce743fb9a2: Subfigure Labels in Multipart Figures and Tables
elements.2211.03184_79f738731abb03598be374a6226dc: Multipart figures should be combined and labeled before final submission
elements.2211.03184_7f485969d833f7f2803b56519f954: Labels should appear centered below each subfigure in 8 point Times New Roman font in the format of (a), (b), (c).
elements.2211.03184_9de0bcf168320c81de3fe1be9f8c6: Figures (line artwork or photographs) should be named starting with the first 5 letters of the authorâs last name
elements.2211.03184_f07fa6d918ce41c1e94721afcf448: The next characters in the filename should be the number that represents the sequential location of this image in your article
elements.2211.03184_36e0268b15b8b38d9d810306b919d: paper, the first three figures would be named ander1.tif, ander2.tif, and ander3.ps
elements.2211.03184_fb1dc5c2ae6b112d385ba17b4101b: Tables should contain only the body of the table (not the caption) and should be named similarly to figures, except that `.t' is inserted in-between the authorâs name and the table number
elements.2211.03184_a7fce5f79d747ca598d1740c70818: For example, author Andersonâs first three tables would be named ander.t1.tif, ander.t2.ps, ander.t3.eps.
elements.2211.03184_427a0fb37780960fd86c0ee9a2979: Referencing a Figure or Table Within Your Paper
elements.2211.03184_cc5fdd96ff56ee592e1fae61ca89d: When referencing your figures and tables within your paper, use the abbreviation
elements.2211.03184_afa6f312394ab183d77a6e6ba5c02: even at the beginning of a sentence
elements.2211.03184_7879db42fa5d75f09853863919f5b: Tables should be numbered with Roman Numerals.
elements.2211.03184_c4c5081e7ab27ecc4707ed26852de: Checking Your Figures: The IEEE Graphics Analyzer
elements.2211.03184_8dc656e836e35fa3b5b1845230d7b: The IEEE Graphics Analyzer enables authors to pre-screen their graphics for compliance with IEEE Transactions and Journals standards before submission
elements.2211.03184_718ab88a088b89cf753093384ddb2: The online tool, located at http://graphicsqc.ieee.org/, allows authors to upload their graphics in order to check that each file is the correct file format, resolution, size and colorspace; that no fonts are missing or corrupt; that figures are not compiled in layers or have transparency, and that they are named according to the IEEE Transactions and Journals naming convention
elements.2211.03184_663122d0aa78445fd6c0dc58e3749: At the end of this automated process, authors are provided with a detailed report on each graphic within the web applet, as well as by email
elements.2211.03184_8222e186f6af13ddd70030c41d848: For more information on using the Graphics Analyzer or any other graphics related topic, contact the IEEE Graphics Help Desk by e-mail at graphics@ieee.org.
elements.2211.03184_3574a382cbff61f0ce04a4a755c4a: Because IEEE will do the final formatting of your paper, you do not need to position figures and tables at the top and bottom of each column
elements.2211.03184_d53b8f911150c0499b1874f71b30b: In fact, all figures, figure captions, and tables can be placed at the end of your paper
elements.2211.03184_6ded016e2d66acb5dd7145220ad7e: In addition to, or even in lieu of submitting figures within your final manuscript, figures should be submitted individually, separate from the manuscript in one of the file formats listed above in Section VI-J. Place figure captions below the figures; place table titles above the tables
elements.2211.03184_7381d077a9064405602dcceffc260: Please do not include captions as part of the figures, or put them in
elements.2211.03184_ae5ab5402aa906efbabd6693df2e5: Also, do not place borders around the outside of your figures.
elements.2211.03184_4a9db1e013f5a753594d12c94804b: A conclusion section is not required
elements.2211.03184_b5a3635c886683c692c56e0206d96: Although a conclusion may review the main points of the paper, do not replicate the abstract as the conclusion
elements.2211.03184_fdf945da28ac3dedbf93ca58b9f87: A conclusion might elaborate on the importance of the work or suggest applications and extensions.
elements.2211.03184_9e94e19c5ce63fda58fee69578201: The preferred spelling of the word
elements.2211.03184_e0ee45677d4c5ccb6763891b3b605: in American English is without an

elements.2211.03184_4112f1f0197e8e79dd2f092aeeb6b: One of us (S.B.A.) would like to thank . . . .
elements.2211.03184_af306eabaebd2fadfe1fff91ffbfe: Instead, write âF. A. Author thanks ... .â In most cases, sponsor and financial support acknowledgments are placed in the unnumbered footnote on the first page, not here.
